FBIS4-3534 "drchi078_a_94009" FBIS-CHI-94-078 Daily Report 21 Apr 1994 INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS General Boris Yeltsin, President Clinton Discuss Bosnian Crisis Boris Yeltsin, President Clinton Discuss Bosnian Crisis OW2104195994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1823 GMT 21 Apr 94 OW2104195994 Beijing XINHUA English BFN [Text] Moscow, April 21 (XINHUA) -- A spokesman for Russian President Boris Yeltsin announced here today that the Russian, U.S. presidents and representatives from United Nations and European Union will probably meet within a month over the Bosnian crisis. Yeltsin's press secretary Vyacheslav Kostikov made the announcement at a press conference in the Kremlin today. According to Kostikov, President Yeltsin talked with U.S. President Bill Clinton for 40 minutes over telephone late last night. He said President Yeltsin firmly opposes NATO air strikes at the Bosnian Serb Forces without consulting with Russia. Kostikov added that President Clinton had promised to act with caution in dealing with such matters in the future. Yeltsin on Tuesday [19 April] called on the Serbs to withdraw from around the Muslim enclave of Gorazde, Eastern Bosnia, to allow the deployment of U.N. Peacekeepers.
